<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n06053b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n06" href="#n06053b">N06 (VI.B.11)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n06all.htm#n06053b"> 53(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Mirror inhibits</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">il existe, en outre, une gymnastique sp&eacute;ciale de la volont&eacute;, comme <i>pouvoir d&apos;arr&ecirc;t</i> ou d&apos;inhibition, comme principe r&eacute;pressif des mouvements. &ldquo;En observant les jeux enfantins, on arrive &agrave; cette conviction que plusieurs actions des enfants ont exclusivement pour but l&apos;exercice de la facult&eacute; inhibitoire de la volont&eacute;, ou l&apos;arr&ecirc;t du mouvement existant. C&apos;est ce que montrent, par exemple, <mark>diverses poses immobiles que l&apos;enfant prend devant la glace</mark>, et o&ugrave; celle-ci lui sert &agrave; contr&ocirc;ler son immobilit&eacute;. <font color="green">[There is, moreover, a special gymnastics of the will, as a power of arrest or inhibition, as the repressive principle of the movements. "By observing children&apos;s games, we come to the conviction that many children&apos;s actions are exclusively aimed at the exercise of the inhibitory faculty of the will, or the cessation of the existing movement. This is shown, for example, by various motionless poses that the child takes in front of the mirror, and where it serves to control its immobility.]</font> <small> Fr&eacute;d&eacute;ric Queyrat, <a name="FQLJ" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#FQLJ"><cite title="source">Les Jeux des Enfants</cite></a> (1920) 110</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
